sing record in that span. In 2013, Hayes' last season as head coach, he coached the women's team to a 17\u20136 record, putting together a 12-game win streak that was the third-longest win streak in the country during the 2013 season. Troy entered the Sun Belt Tournament as the #3-seed, but was upset by #6-seed [[Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders|Middle Tennessee]] in the quarterfinals.\n\nRawia Elsisi, a former Troy women's tennis player, was hired in 2014 as the next head coach for the team. In her first season at the helm, she led the Trojans to a 15\u20138 record that included a win over then #72-ranked [[Nicholls State Colonels|Nicholls State]] and received the #4-seed in the Sun Belt Tournament. Troy defeated [[Texas State Bobcats|Texas State]] in the quarterfinals of tournament, only to drop their semifinal match to #66 [[Georgia State Panthers|Georgia State]].\n\nIn 2018, Troy garnered their first ever #1-seed into the Sun Belt Tournament by way of a 4-2 conference record during the season, despite finishing the regular season with an 8\u201310 record. Troy had gone a 6-game win streak toward the end of the season, which included a 4\u20133 win over eventual Sun Belt champion Georgia State. The Trojans won their first round match of the Sun Belt Tournament against #9-seed [[Georgia Southern Eagles|Georgia Southern]] but lost their semifinal match to #4-seed [[South Alabama Jaguars|South Alabama]].\n\n==Award Winners/Finalists==\n*'''[[NCAA Woman of the Year Award]] Finalist'''\n:Rawia Elsisi \u2013 2009\n\n*'''[[Atlantic Sun Conference]] Coach of the Year'''\n:Eric Hayes - 2004\n\n*'''[[Sun Belt Conference]] Coach of the Year'''\n:Rawia Elsisi - 2018\n\n==ITA Final Rankings==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#8e0028; color:white;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#8e0028; color:white;\" | Record\n! style=\"background:#8e0028; color:white;\" | ITA<br>National<br>Ranking\n! style=\"background:#8e0028; color:white;\" | ITA<br>Regional<br>Ranking\n|-